<DOC><DOCNO> AP890724-0082 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1359EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-China-Floods     07-24 0291</FIRST><SECOND>AM-China-Floods,0303</SECOND><HEAD>Floods Batter China, 117 More Dead</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Heavy rain in northern China touched off floodsand landslides that killed at least 117 people, destroyed thousandsof buildings, and ravaged crops, official reports said Monday.   Some of the deaths were caused by Typhoon Hope, which struckChina on Thursday. Up to 14 inches of rain has fallen in someplaces, the English-language China Daily said.   At least 1,400 flood-related deaths already have been reportedin China this summer.   The China Daily said 41 people were killed and 381 peopleinjured in landslides caused by torrential rains last week inDandong, in the northeastern province of Liaoning.   The rail line between Dandong, a coastal city on the NorthKorean border, and the provincial capital of Shenyang was washedout in 65 places, the report said. More than 16,000 buildings weredestroyed.   In neighboring Jilin province, 43 people have died sinceSaturday in floods and mudslides, the China Youth News said. Italso reported 22 people missing.   Typhoon Hope killed 21 people in Zhejiang province and 36 inFujian province, the China Daily said.   In Fujian's Zhanghe county, 4,000 homes were destroyed,authorities said. At least 8,151 acres of crops, 12,500 tons ofgrain, and 1,000 pigs were washed away since Saturday, they said.   The storm also cut telecommunications and transport in that area.   Heavy rains and mudslides in northern China have killed fourpeople in Beijing, according to previous reports. China Daily said12 people still were missing in Fengjiayuan, near Beijing, after amudslide Saturday.   Flooding has been severe in southern and central China since thebeginning of June.   Yang Zhenhuai, deputy director of the State Flood ControlHeadquarters, said about 2,700 people die annually in floods.</TEXT></DOC>